"It's not about heroism, it's about sincerity. It may be a funny idea, but the only way to fight the plague is sincerity. "

"What does sincerity mean? "

"I don't know what sincerity usually means. But in my case, I know sincerity means doing your job. "

Albert Camus, the plague

Starting in Shanghai, arriving at the Albert Camus Hospital and working in isolation wards in recent days, I wondered what "sincerity" was all about, as the channel of news of the outbreak shifted from the online media to a more visceral experience.

Sincerity is certainly not a person's sincerity, is not a social role of sincerity.

It's everyone's.

Dr. Zhang Wenhong said: "This disease if only the doctor looks, is impossible to look good. "

This outbreak, linked to the fate of the entire country and many individuals. Suffering, life and death, love, humanity, morality, conscience, feelings, responsibility, struggle, are all being re-examined one by one.

Before the psychological construction is completed, the role transformation has already been completed. From the healthy crowd to the sick, from 996 office workers to Otaku men Otaku women, from the People's teachers to the network anchor. In this battle, we need each and every one of us, to take on a role in society, to come together with sincerity.

Let us say that sincerity here is quiet, is responsible, is faith, is unity, is hope, is optimistic, is a panacea. You could say you're staying in, you're swimming upstream. There is a thousand sincerity in a thousand Hamlett, and what is the sincerity in your heart?

I'll start with two "sincerities. ".

My Ward has a 90-year-old old old man, gray hair, people are thin and small, slow reaction, teeth lost few, a dialect I and colleagues listen to is confused. We put food to mouth, can understand his "just do not move (eat not move) . ".

Do not eat nutrition can not keep up with, resistance will be worse and worse. My colleagues and I carefully pick out the fish bones, and then pound into Surimi, mixed into the rice bubble, it will be carefully pounded to better swallow. Only half a teaspoon at a time to prevent coughing. The old man sipped his lips in cooperation and went back and forth to estimate that half an hour had passed. He waved his hand and signalled that he would not eat any more. While we were sorting through the garbage, he gave us a big, goofy smile.

That's a nice touch. That's a lovely gesture.

Maybe he was laughing across the language barrier to express his thanks to our medical staff; maybe he was tired of staring at the wall of white flowers every day, seeing two white flowers "big white" come in to work, feel interesting; Maybe he's just embarrassed that his teeth are falling out and he eats slowly.

In any case, the sincerity of his moment gave me the strength to work honestly.

(photo by Xiao Junwei)

The other, I found in the group when I was editing the video.

In the video, an old woman in a purple cotton-padded Jacket, excitedly murmuring, "I am so relieved to have you. With you I have hope. Thank you. " Her voice is loud and Hoarse, said in front and out of the window of the two medical staff vigorously Bizan, salute.

Under the heavy cotton-padded jacket, the aunt's saluting action is emotional, forceful and standard.

I marveled at aunt's optimism and positivity in the face of disaster, and moved her to express her gratitude in the truest and plainest way.

Still, it's this lovely earnestness.
